  "text": "The Kubernetes API server write chain from API handler to etcd storage works as follows:\n\n1. REST Handler (staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/endpoints/handlers/create.go):\nThe `createHandler` function processes HTTP POST requests for resource creation. At line 184, it calls `r.Create()` on the REST resource interface, passing the context, object name, decoded object, and creation options.\n\n2. Registry Store (staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/registry/generic/registry/store.go):\nThe `Store.Create()` method (line 446) is called by REST handlers for all resource types. This is the generic registry implementation that validates the object and prepares it for storage. At line 526, it delegates to the underlying storage backend by calling `e.Storage.Create(ctx, key, obj, out, ttl, dryrun.IsDryRun(options.DryRun))`.\n\n3. Pod Storage (pkg/registry/core/pod/storage/storage.go):\nThe Pod storage implementation demonstrates how specific resource types integrate with the generic Store. The `NewStorage` function (line 72) creates a `genericregistry.Store` configured with Pod-specific strategies and options. This store is then wrapped in the `REST` struct (line 66) which implements the REST interface.\n\n4. etcd3 Store (staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/etcd3/store.go):\nThe `store.Create()` method (line 241) implements the `storage.Interface` for etcd3 backend. It performs several key operations:\n- Line 260: Encodes the object using `runtime.Encode(s.codec, obj)` - this calls the Codec serialization to convert the Go object to bytes\n- Line 283: Calls `s.client.Kubernetes.OptimisticPut()` with the serialized data\n\n5. etcd Client - OptimisticPut (client/v3/kubernetes/client.go in etcd-io/etcd):\nThe `Client.OptimisticPut()` method (line 83) creates an etcd transaction. It uses the etcd v3 client to create a transaction that compares the key's revision and then executes a Put operation (line 87: `clientv3.OpPut(key, string(value), clientv3.WithLease(opts.LeaseID))`). Finally at line 94, it commits the transaction with `txn.Commit()`.\n\n6. etcd Client - OpPut (client/v3/op.go in etcd-io/etcd):\nThe `OpPut()` function (line 271) creates an Op struct representing a Put operation. It encapsulates the key, value, and options (like lease ID). The operation is later converted to a protobuf `PutRequest` in the `toRequestOp()` method (lines 192-194), which is sent to the etcd server.\n\nThe complete write chain ensures that: (1) HTTP requests are parsed and validated by the API server, (2) the generic registry applies Kubernetes-specific validation and strategies, (3) objects are serialized to bytes using configured codecs, and (4) the serialized data is written to etcd using optimistic locking to handle concurrent updates."
}

